[
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: France seeks stable security in the west while avoiding an unnecessary naval gamble in the Channel. I will keep my forces defensive along the north and press for shared containment of German ambitions on the continent. I propose neutrality between England and France at sea for the moment — I will not thrust F BRE into ENG or LON without clear English intent, and I ask England to avoid provoking a naval duel with me. On land, I plan to position my armies to cover Paris and the Alpine approaches; any continental squeeze toward Germany should be coordinated to avoid leaving Iberia or the Mediterranean exposed. Diplomatically I am open to a limited, focused cooperation against German overreach (particularly in Belgium and the Rhineland) rather than broad commitments in the Channel."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "England",
    "content": "My English friend: let us be frank and efficient. I will hold F BRE from aggressive moves toward LON this turn if you refrain from sending F LON or F EDI into ENG/MAO aimed at challenging my presence. A simple non-aggression at sea gives us both flexibility: I free your fleets to guard the North and you reduce the risk of France-England naval conflict. Forecast implication: based on the available intelligence artifact, there is a tangible 60%+ chance Germany will test Belgium or the Channel approaches this year; keeping our naval posture neutral reduces accidental escalation. If Germany makes a continental opening toward Belgium or Luxembourg, I will be prepared to coordinate with you to blunt them — but I will not commit to a fleet war for English gains in the Channel. Acceptable immediate moves: F BRE HOLD / A PAR SUPPORT F BRE or F BRE - PIC (as reassurance). Let's keep trade routes calm and focus on a coordinated response only if Germany actually advances."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "Germany",
    "content": "Herr Germany: France wishes to avoid needless confrontation. I will maintain a posture that protects Paris and my southern approaches. However, should you test Belgium or threaten our shared border, I will respond firmly. Forecast implication: the STORYWORLD_FORECAST_ARTIFACT indicates a significant probability (≈60%) of German maneuvers opening westward; I treat that as a high-confidence signal and will plan accordingly. I therefore propose a simple understanding: if your moves are defensive and aimed east or north (not Belgium or Picardy), we stay neutral toward one another. Any incursion through Belgium or a thrust into Picardy will be met with French force. This is your chance to avoid a two-front diplomatic problem."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "Italy",
    "content": "Italia: I value our cordial ties. I do not intend to contest your holdings in the south; my focus is securing Paris and the Channel flanks. If you can avoid moves into Provence or Piedmont for now, I will not press into Tyrolia or the western Alps. Consider a local non-aggression: A MAR and A PAR can be used to support limited advances into Burgundy if you prefer, but I favor holding MAR and PAR for now to deter German pressure from the north. This helps both of us conserve units for future bargaining over Iberia or the Mediterranean."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "Spain",
    "content": "To the power of Iberia (via diplomatic channel): France recognizes the unique leverage Spain/Portugal can offer. If you are willing to coordinate — or at least refrain from sudden moves into southern France — I can offer tacit tolerance of Spanish naval moves in the Atlantic and promise not to contest Portugal this season. Forecast implication: the current artifact suggests Germany may seek openings elsewhere; a stable Iberian front reduces the chance of Germany exploiting a southern flank. Let us discuss limited, confidence-building moves that ensure Iberian independence and keep the western approaches calm."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "Austria",
    "content": "Austria: France does not seek confrontation in the east. I will not interfere with your positions in the Balkans so long as you do not attempt to encourage German aggression westward. Should Austria find itself threatened by Russia, communicate and I will weigh measures to prevent a wider continental chain reaction. My immediate intent is defensive; please reciprocate by avoiding diplomatic pressure on Germany that could drive them toward Belgium."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "Russia",
    "content": "To Russia: I respect your strength in the east and wish no quarrel. My priority is German containment without destabilizing the Mediterranean. If you press Austria or Germany aggressively, warn me — I will not risk Paris lightly, but I can coordinate to ensure Germany cannot exploit gaps between our fronts. Forecast implication: given the artifact’s elevated probability of German westward action (~60%), it is prudent for us to maintain open lines: France will hold its positions in the north unless Germany moves into Belgium, at which point I will act swiftly. Please avoid premature southern campaigns that might push Austria into a German alliance against us."
  }
]

